The 30-days moving average of the Nigeria external reserves dipped by 1.6 per cent in less than two months to $35.99 billion as at July 23, 2020, as the value of the naira dipped last week at both the parallel market and the Nigeria Autonomous Foreign Exchange market (NAFEX). The reserves which had trended downwards since the beginning of the year dropping to $33.44 billion in April, had gotten a boost in May,  the back of the disbursement by the IMFof the $3.4 billion it granted within its Rapid Financing Instrument (RFI). It had however, begun a depletion as economic activities resumed fully in June depleting by $575.79 million or 1.56 per cent between June 1, 2020 and July 23, 2020. On June 1, the 30 days moving average of the reserves stood at $36.57 billion before depleting to $35.99 billion as at July 23, 2020. Oil producing and exporting countries had agreed to relax production cuts to 7.7 million barrels per day effective from August as oil continues to trade above $40.0/bbl., reaching a 4-month high of $44.1/bbl. as of  July 23, as economic activities continued to improve despite the spike in COVID-19 cases. Also, the CBN continued its weekly intervention into the Secondary Market Intervention Sales (SMIS) Wholesale Window, offering a total of $100.0m for the week. According to foreign exchange analysts, the position of the of the reserves would have been worse had it not been for the fall in import demand and for the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN)’s temporary halt to foreign exchange sales to bureau de change. Although BDCs have urged that the CBN resume sale of forex to them, the CBN had held back on the three times a week dollar sales to the BDC, intervening only at the official end of the forex market where the value of the naira remains stable at N381 to the dollar. Last week, the naira had further weakened shedding N2 and N1 from its value at both the parallel market and the NAFEX. From N470 which the naira sold against the dollar, the previous week, it weakened to N472 to the dollar, while at the Importers and Exporters window (I&E), the NAFEX rate dropped to N389.50 to the dollar. Activity at the I&E had also weakened declining by 33.2 per cent last week to close at $130.3 million. At the FMDQ Securities Exchange Forex Futures Contract Market, the total value of open contracts appreciated 22bps week on week to $13.6 billion. The SEP 2020 instrument at contract price of N396.48, recorded the most buying interest with additional $17.1 million for the week, taking its total value to $1.2billion. Likewise, the JAN 2021 instrument at contract price of N407.30 saw the least subscription of $1.7 million, bringing its total value to $1.2 billion. This week, traders said they expect the naira to trade at a similar band on the back of sustained CBN intervention sale to the forex segments. Traders said they also expect the CBN to keep up its liquidity mopping auctions as maturities hit the market this week. Maturities worth N20.1 billion and N266 million from the Open Market Operations and Treasury Bills markets respectively as well as bond coupon payment worth N49.6 billion is expected to hit the system this week. Last week, system liquidity opened at N86.9 billion, while open buy back and overnight rates opened at 9.2 and 10.7 per cents respectively, lower than the previous week close of 20.3 and 21.8 per cents. By the close of the week, OBB and OVN rates printed at 1.6 and 2.2 respectively as system liquidity settled at N963.1 billion. In the T-bills secondary segment, performance was bullish as average yield across tenors dipped 7bps week on week to 2.0 per cent from 2.1 per cent. The 91-day instrument saw the most buying interest with rates lowering 50bps. Similarly, rates on the 182- day declined 28bps, while the 364-day instrument closed flat.